ğŸ”„ Linux Input & Output Redirection + Pipes
ğŸ§  1. What is Redirection?
By default, Linux programs:

Read input from: stdin (keyboard)

Send output to: stdout (your screen)

Send errors to: stderr (also screen)

We can redirect any of these to/from files or programs.

ğŸ“¤ Output Redirection
âœ… Overwrite output to a file:
bash
Copy
Edit
command > file.txt
Replaces old content

Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
sort names.txt > sorted.txt
âœ… Append output to a file:
bash
Copy
Edit
command >> file.txt
Keeps old content, adds new below

ğŸ“Œ Standard Output vs. Error Output
Descriptor	Name	Symbol	Example
1	stdout	1>	command 1> out.txt
2	stderr	2>	command 2> error.txt

ğŸš« Redirect Errors to /dev/null (black hole)
bash
Copy
Edit
command 2> /dev/null
Hides all warnings and errors

ğŸ“¥ Input Redirection
âœ… Read input from a file
bash
Copy
Edit
command < input.txt
Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
sort < names.txt
ğŸ§¾ Summary of Redirection
Task	Symbol	Example
Redirect stdout	>	ls > list.txt
Append stdout	>>	echo "Done" >> log.txt
Redirect stderr	2>	grep something file 2> error.log
Redirect both stdout and stderr	> file 2>&1	command > all.txt 2>&1
Redirect stdin	<	sort < unsorted.txt
Discard stderr	2> /dev/null	grep root /etc/* 2> /dev/null

ğŸ“¬ Here Document (Multi-line input)
bash
Copy
Edit
command <<EOF
line 1
line 2
EOF
Use any word instead of EOF (e.g. END, INPUT)

Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
cat <<EOF
Hello
Multiline Input
EOF
ğŸ“® Here String (Single-line input)
bash
Copy
Edit
command <<< "your text here"
Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
bc <<< "5+3"
ğŸ§ª Combine grep + sort + column (with Pipe)
Problem: Too many lines â†’ unreadable output
Solution: Chain commands using |
bash
Copy
Edit
grep -v '^#' config.txt | sort | column -t
Symbol	Meaning
`	`

Each program:

Reads from the left

Processes the data

Passes it to the program on the right

ğŸ§ª Practice Exercise (Hands-On)
ğŸ§° Create test files
